{{About||the general concept of dress|Clothing|other uses}} {{Redirect|Dresses|the song by Betty Blowtorch|Betty Blowtorch#Discography}} {{merge from| Basic dress|date=July 2018}} {{merge from|Bodycon dress|date=July 2018}} {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}
[[File:Apricot_Dress_worn_by_Jacqueline_Kennedy_for_a_daytime_boat_ride_on_Lake_Pichola,_India.jpg|thumb|Apricot-colored dress worn by [[Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis|Jacqueline Kennedy]].]] A '''dress''' (also known as a '''[[frock]]''' or a '''[[gown]]''') is a garment consisting of a [[skirt]] with an attached [[bodice]] (or a matching bodice giving the effect of a one-piece garment).<ref>{{cite book|last1=Condra|first1=Jill|title=The Greenwood Encyclopedia of Clothing Through World History: 1801 to the present|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=9780313336652|page=59|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=q6FI2czFz6MC&pg=PA59|language=en}}</ref> It consists of a top piece that covers the torso and hangs down over the legs. A dress can be any one-piece garment containing a skirt of any length. Dresses can be formal or informal. In many cultures, dresses are more often worn by women and girls.
The [[hemline]]s of dresses vary depending on the [[fashion]] of the time period and the [[modesty]] or personal taste of the wearer.<ref name="Davis2007">{{cite book|last=Davis|first=Michael|title=Art of dress designing|year=2007|publisher=Global Media|location=Delhi|isbn=81-904575-7-8|edition=1st}}</ref>
== About == Dresses are outer garments made up of a [[bodice]] and a [[skirt]] and can be made in one or more pieces.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dictionary.com/browse/dress|title=The definition of dress|last=|first=|date=|website=Dictionary.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-01-29}}</ref>{{Sfn|Picken|1957|p=101}} Dresses are generally suitable for both general and [[formal wear]] in the West for women and children.{{Sfn|Picken|1957|p=101}}
Historically, dresses could also include other items of clothing such as [[corset]]s, [[kirtle]]s, [[partlet]]s, [[petticoat]]s, smocks and [[stomacher]]s.{{Sfn|Edwards|2017|p=20}}{{Sfn|Cunningham|2003|p=20}}{{Sfn|Edwards|2017|p=30}}
==History==
=== 11th century === In the 11th century, women in [[Europe]] wore dresses that were similar to men's tunics and were loose, with a hemline reaching to below the knees or lower.{{Sfn|Newman|2001|p=113}} By the end of the century, these dresses featured a tighter fit on the arms and women's upper bodies.{{Sfn|Newman|2001|p=113}} Dresses were made snug by featuring slits on the sides of the dress that were pulled tight in order to fit a woman's figure.{{Sfn|Newman|2001|p=114}}
=== 16th century === Starting in the 1550s, middle- and upper-class women in Europe wore dresses which included a smock, stays, [[kirtle]], [[gown]], forepart, sleeves, ruff and a [[partlet]].{{Sfn|Edwards|2017|p=20}} Undergarments were not worn underneath.{{Sfn|Edwards|2017|p=20}} In England, [[Elizabeth I of England|Queen Elizabeth]] dictated what kinds of dresses women were allowed to wear.{{Sfn|Edwards|2017|p=21}} French women were inspired by Spanish-style [[bodice]]s and also wore [[Ruff (clothing)|ruffs]].{{Sfn|Edwards|2017|p=21}} French dresses were known as ''marlottes''.{{Sfn|Bigelow|1970|p=110}} In Italy, dresses were known as ''ropa'' and ''semarra.''{{Sfn|Bigelow|1970|p=110}} Dresses in the 16th century also displayed surface decoration such as [[embroidery]], with [[blackwork]] being especially popular.{{Sfn|Edwards|2017|p=23}}
Women's dresses in [[Russia]] during both the 16th and 17th centuries identified a woman's place in society or their family.{{Sfn|Pushkareva|1997|p=120}}
=== 17th century === [[Holland]], as a center of textile production, was a particularly noted area of innovation in dress during this time period.{{Sfn|Edwards|2017|p=30}} During this time period, in Spain and Portugal, women wore [[stomacher]]s.{{Sfn|Edwards|2017|p=30}} However, in England and France, dresses became more "naturally" shaped.{{Sfn|Edwards|2017|p=30}} Lace and slashing were popular decorations.{{Sfn|Edwards|2017|p=30}} Skirts were full, with regular folds and the overskirt allowed the display of an underskirt of contrasting fabric.{{Sfn|Edwards|2017|p=30}} Necklines became lower as well.{{Sfn|Edwards|2017|p=30}} Embroidery that reflected scientific discoveries, such as new animals and plants discovered were popular.{{Sfn|Edwards|2017|p=34}} In the [[British colonization of the Americas|British Colonies]], the multiple-piece dresses were also popular, though less luxurious.{{Sfn|Staples|Shaw|2013|p=222}} Wealthy women living in the Spanish or Dutch colonies in the Americas copied the fashions that were popular from their homelands.{{Sfn|Havelin|2012|p=27}}
The three-piece dress, which had a bodice, petticoat and gown, were popular until the last 25 years, in which the [[Mantua (clothing)|mantua]], or a one-piece gown, became more popular.{{Sfn|Edwards|2017|p=35}} [[Corset]]s became more important in dresses by the 1680s.{{Sfn|Bigelow|1970|p=126}}
Working women, and women in [[Slavery in the United States|slavery in the Americas]], used simple patterns to create shifts, wool or linen petticoats and gowns and cotton dresses.{{Sfn|Havelin|2012|p=26}} The bottoms of the skirts could be tucked into the waistband when a woman was near fire when near a cooking or heating source.{{Sfn|Havelin|2012|p=26}}
=== 18th century === [[File:Vestido,_Século_XIX_(1870-80),_MN_Traje.tif|thumb|Dress, (1870-1880) from the [[National Museum of Costume and Fashion]] in Portugal.]] Large, triangular silhouettes were favored during the 18th century, skirts were wide and supported by hoop underskirts.{{Sfn|Bigelow|1970|p=135}}{{Sfn|Bigelow|1970|p=137}} One-piece gowns remained popular until the middle of the century.{{Sfn|Edwards|2017|p=49}} During the 1760s in France, hoop petticoats were reduced in size.{{Sfn|Pietsch|2013|p=400}} Lighter colors and lighter fabrics were also favored.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=funk&AN=CO225700&site=ehost-live|title=Funk & Wagnalls New World Encyclopedia|last=|first=|publisher=|year=2017|isbn=|location=|pages=|chapter=Costume|subscription=yes|via=EBSCOhost}}</ref> In Colonial America, women most often wore a gown and petticoat, in which the skirt of the gown opened to reveal the [[petticoat]] underneath.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=http://www.history.org/history/clothing/women/wglossary.cfm|title=A Colonial Lady's Clothing: A Glossary of Terms|last=|first=|date=|website=Colonial Williamsburg|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-01-24}}</ref> Women also had [[riding habit]]s which consisted of the petticoat, jacket and a waistcoat.<ref name=":2" />
French fashion regarding dresses became very fast-changing during the later part of the 18th century.{{Sfn|Pietsch|2013|p=397-398}} Throughout this period, the length of fashionable dresses varied only slightly, between ankle-length and floor-sweeping.<ref name="Davis2007" /> Between 1740 and 1770, the ''[[Sack-back gown|robe à la française]]'' was very popular with upper-class women.{{Sfn|Delpierre|1997|p=15-16}} In France, the [[Empire style]] became popular after the [[French Revolution]].<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=https://www.makers.com/blog/brief-history-womens-fashion-photo-gallery|title=A Brief History of Women's Fashion|last=|first=|date=7 September 2016|work=Makers|access-date=2018-01-24|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en}}</ref> This style was more simple and was also favored by [[Empress Joséphine|Josephine Bonaparte]].<ref name=":1" /> Other types of dresses that were popular during the revolution included tunic dresses and the ''negligée à la patriot,'' which featured the red, white and blue colors, symbolic of the revolution.{{Sfn|Bigelow|1970|p=157}}
===19th century=== [[File:Dress_(AM_11988-3).jpg|alt=Early 19th century dress.|left|thumb|Early 19th century dress.]] Women's dresses in the 19th century began to be classified by the time of day or purpose of the dress.{{Sfn|Bigelow|1970|p=183}} High-waisted dresses were popular until around 1830.{{Sfn|Bigelow|1970|p=183}}
Early nineteenth century dresses in Russia were influenced by [[Classicism]] and were made of thin fabrics, with some dresses being semi-transparent.{{Sfn|Pushkareva|1997|p=242}} [[Élisabeth Vigée Le Brun|Elizabeth Vigée Le Brun]] wore these types of dresses with a short skirt (reaching to her ankles) when she lived in Russia between 1785 and 1801.{{Sfn|Pushkareva|1997|p=242}} Many Russian women copied her style.{{Sfn|Pushkareva|1997|p=242}} By the 1840s, Russian women were turning to what was in fashion in Europe.{{Sfn|Pushkareva|1997|p=244}}
Europeans styles in dresses increased dramatically to the [[hoopskirt]] and [[crinoline]]-supported styles of the 1860s,{{Sfn|Krohn|2012|p=36}} then fullness was draped and drawn to the back.{{Sfn|Bigelow|1970|p=188}} Dresses had a "day" bodice with a high [[neckline]] and long sleeves, and an "evening" bodice with a low neckline ([[decollete]]) and very short sleeves. In Russia, metal hoopskirts were known as "malakhovs."{{Sfn|Pushkareva|1997|p=244}} Skirts of the 1860s were heavily decorated.{{Sfn|Bigelow|1970|p=188}}
To sleep, women in the American West wore floor-length dresses of white [[cotton]] with high collars displaying decoration.{{Sfn|Krohn|2012|p=37}} Various [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] people, such as the [[Navajo]] and the [[Mescalero|Mescalero Apache]] began to adapt the designs of their dresses to look more like the European Americans they came in contact with.{{Sfn|Parezo|Jones|2009|p=384}} Navajo women further adapted the European designs, incorporating their own sense of beauty, "creating ''hózhó."''{{Sfn|Parezo|Jones|2009|p=384-385}}
Paper [[Pattern (sewing)|sewing patterns]] for women to sew their own dresses started to be readily available in the 1860s, when the [[Butterick Publishing Company]] began to promote them.{{Sfn|Darnell|2000|p=27}} These patterns were graded by size, which was a new innovation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://butterick.mccall.com/our-company/butterick-history|title=Butterick History|last=|first=|date=|website=Butterick Patterns|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-01-24}}</ref>
The [[Victorian era|Victorian era's]] dresses were tight-fitting and decorated with pleats, [[Gather (knitting)|rouching]] and frills.<ref name=":1" /> Women in the United States who were involved in [[Victorian dress reform|dress reform]] in the 1850s found themselves the center of attention, both positive and negative.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oIro7MtiFuYC&lpg=PA72&pg=PA72&q=women's%20dress%20history|title=Encyclopedia of Women's History in America|last=Cullen-DuPont|first=Kathryn|publisher=Infobase Publishing|year=2014|isbn=9781438110332|location=|pages=71–72|language=en}}</ref> By 1881, the [[Rational Dress Society]] had formed in reaction to the restrictive dress of the era.<ref name=":1" />
===20th century=== [[File:Model_posing_in_a_glamorous_1930s_evening_gown_(4522097205).jpg|alt=Model posing in a glamorous 1930s evening gown.|thumb|324x324px|Model posing in a glamorous 1930s evening gown.]] In the early twentieth century, the look popularized by the [[Gibson Girl]] was fashionable.{{Sfn|Darnell|2000|p=9}} The upper part of women's dresses in the [[Edwardian era]] included a "pigeon breast" look that gave way to a corseted waist and an s-shaped silhouette.{{Sfn|Darnell|2000|p=9}} Women called their dresses "waists" if one-piece, or "[[Shirtdress|shirtwaists]]," if it consisted of a skirt and a blouse.{{Sfn|Darnell|2000|p=11}} The bodice of the dresses had a boned lining.{{Sfn|Darnell|2000|p=11}} Informally, wealthy women wore [[tea gown]]s at home.{{Sfn|Darnell|2000|p=13}} These garments were looser, though not as loose as a "wrapper," and made of expensive fabric and laces.{{Sfn|Darnell|2000|p=13}}
By 1910, the Edwardian look was replaced with a straighter silhouette.{{Sfn|Darnell|2000|p=49}} French designer, [[Paul Poiret]], had a huge impact on the look of the time.{{Sfn|Darnell|2000|p=49}} Designs developed by Poiret were available in both boutiques and also in [[department store]]s.{{Sfn|Darnell|2000|p=50}} Popular dresses of the time were one-piece and included [[lingerie dress]]es which could be layered.{{Sfn|Darnell|2000|p=53}} At around the same time, in the United States, the [[American Ladies Tailors' Association]] developed a dress called the [[suffragette suit]], which was practical for women to work and move around in.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://onlinemba.unc.edu/blog/Feminist-History-in-Womens-Work-Suits/|title=100 Years of Feminist History Explained in 10 Women’s Work Suits|last=Greenberg|first=Molly|date=2017-03-01|work=UNC|access-date=2018-01-24|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mariefranceasia.com/my/fashion-my/trends-and-tips-my/trend-guide-my/history-of-pantsuit-218771.html#item=1|title=The fascinating history and evolution of the female pantsuit|last=Khan|first=Sarah|date=2016-11-16|work=Marie France Asia|access-date=2018-01-24|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en-US}}</ref> Another innovation of the 1910s was the ready availability of factory-made clothing.{{Sfn|Richards|2010|p=100}}
Waistlines started out high and by 1915 were below the natural waist.{{Sfn|Darnell|2000|p=53}} By 1920, waistlines were at hip-level.{{Sfn|Darnell|2000|p=53}} Between 1910 and 1920 necklines were lower and dresses could be short-sleeved or sleeveless.{{Sfn|Darnell|2000|p=57}} Women who worked during [[World War I]] preferred shorter dresses, which eventually became the dominant style overall.<ref name=":0" /> In addition to the shorter dresses, waistlines were looser and the dominant colors were black, white and gray.{{Sfn|Richards|2010|p=100-101}}
By 1920, the "new woman" was a trend that saw lighter fabrics and dresses that were easier to put on.{{Sfn|Darnell|2000|p=73}} Younger women were also setting the trends that older women started to follow.{{Sfn|Darnell|2000|p=73}} The dresses of the 1920s could be pulled over the head, were short and straight.{{Sfn|Darnell|2000|p=77}} It was acceptable to wear sleeveless dresses during the day.{{Sfn|Darnell|2000|p=77}} [[Flapper]] dresses were popular until end of the decade.{{Sfn|Darnell|2000|p=105}}
During [[World War II]], dresses were slimmer and inspired by military uniforms.<ref name=":1" /> After WWII, the New Look, promoted by [[Christian Dior]] was very influential on fashion and the look of women's dresses for about a decade.{{Sfn|Parezo|Jones|2009|p=383}}
Since the 1970s, no one dress type or length has dominated fashion for long, with short and ankle-length styles often appearing side-by-side in fashion magazines and catalogs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://womenshistorynetwork.org/blog/?p=2804|title=The History of Hemlines|date=2013-09-01|work=Women's History Network|access-date=2018-01-24|language=en-GB}}</ref>
==Use== {{Western dress codes}} In most varieties of [[formal wear|formal]] [[dress code (Western)|dress codes]] in Western cultures, a dress of an appropriate style is mandatory for women. They are also very popular for special occasions such as [[prom]]s or [[wedding]]s.<ref>{{cite book|last=Pundir|first=Nirupama|title=Fashion technology : today and tomorrow|year=2007|publisher=Mittal Publications|location=New Delhi|isbn=81-8324-203-0}}</ref> For such occasions they, together with [[blouse]] and [[skirt]], remain the de facto standard attire for many girls and women.
